SIMPLE: salmagundi
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Salmagundi
<hw>Sal`ma*gun"di</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>salmigondis</ets>, of uncertain origin; perhaps from L.
<ets>salgama condita</ets>, pl.; <ets>salgama</ets> pickles +
<ets>condita</ets> preserved (see <er>Condite</er>); or from the
Countess <ets>Salmagondi</ets>, lady of honor to Maria de Medici, who is
said to have invented it; or cf. It. <ets>salame</ets> salt meat, and F.
<ets>salmis</ets> a ragout.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mixture of chopped
meat and pickled herring, with oil, vinegar, pepper, and onions.</def>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a mixture of various ingredients; an olio or
medley; a potpourri; a miscellany.</def> <rj><au>W.
Irving.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Salmi</ent>⟦br⟧
